T1  - Golly, A Black Sherlock Holmes!: Race, Cross‐Promotion, and Robertson's Golliwog
AN  - 2376758992
AB  - Produced in the 1950s as a promotional item by a British jam manufacturer, Robertson's, Detective Golly's Hand‐Book with Some Hints for Young Sleuths is a colorful eight‐page children's book offering Detective Golly's safety advice for children.3 Children are given tips on road safety and observation tests, suggestions for assisting the police, and other ways to prevent crimes and solve mysteries. They learn how to design and share secret codes with their friends, fashion disguises, identify tracks and follow trails, and identify counterfeit money. The protagonist is Robertson's corporate mascot, the Golliwog, a character with a long and complicated history. Although the Golliwog is “the least known of the major antiblack caricatures in the United States” (Pilgrim), he has been one of Britain's most popular black stereotypes since his introduction in Florence K. Upton's children's book, Two Dutch Dolls and a Golliwogg (1895).4 Popularity has not kept the Golliwog from accusations of racism; however, with The Guardian 's John Sutherland proclaiming in 2001 the Golliwog was a “racist icon,” “offensive, and now obsolete.”  Pictures first encountered in childhood “linger” in our imaginations and affect our adult actions and ideas, “even if we don't recognize them on a conscious level” (Nel 15). So, what can Detective Golly tell us about Sherlock Holmes, whiteness, and British heritage? What can he tell us about racial attitudes in the United Kingdom in the 1950s when it was published? And, perhaps even more importantly, what can Detective Golly 's racial legacy tell us about current political movements like the UK Independence Party and the role of race and immigration in Brexit today? Ultimately, Detective Golly 's ties to the Golliwog's century‐long racist history and midcentury fears regarding colonial immigration reaffirm Britain's white cultural values rather than challenge them.
